      "writtenOn": "2021-05-18T06:34:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I looked into this. chromeos-base/chromeos-osrelease package contains /etc/os-release.d/*, and it is depended by target-chrome-os/target-chrome-os package.\nhttps://source.corp.google.com/chromeos_internal/src/private-overlays/chromeos-overlay/virtual/target-chrome-os/target-chrome-os-1.3.ebuild;l\u003d62\n\nNote that there is a different virtual package for \"Chromium OS\":\nhttps://source.corp.google.com/chromeos_public/src/third_party/chromiumos-overlay/virtual/target-chromium-os/target-chromium-os-9999.ebuild\n\nThat is why /etc/os-release.d (and /etc/os-release) doesn\u0027t exist on amd64-generic. It is a public board (Chromium OS).\n\nConsidering this, I suspect that that using \"tast_vm\" in this definition is actually wrong because we can run Chrome OS images on VM (e.g. betty). Can we use \"internal\" USE flag instead? IIUC it is a USE flag that is enabled for private boards.\n\nAlso, can you leave a code comment mentioning why we need additional USE flags to define fwupd software feature, also mentioning when we can remove the workaround (you mentioned in this review comment thread, and I think it\u0027s very useful as code comments).",
      "parentUuid": "52078879_394b9507",
      "range": {
